  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Mary Anne Estlin expresses gratification by the visit of William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass. She praises Garrison&apos;s patient manner and his zeal. Emphasizes the influence of Christian teaching on Garrison&apos;s ideas and actions. Garrison was generally surrounded by intense sympathizers. However, Mary A. Estlin tried to get friends who were infected by the British &amp; Foreign Anti-Slavery Society to meet him. Mary A. Estlin read in the Liberator the complimentary notice of her father&apos;s pamphlet. She comments: &quot;Here it does just the work he designed it for.&quot; Frederick Douglass, wherever he goes, &quot;arouses sympathy in your cause &amp; love for himself.&quot; Articles for the Boston bazaar are beginning to pour in. Frederick Douglass will speak again at a meeting tomorrow and the Auxiliary League is to be formed.</subfield>
